  "text": "The GCC stack clash protection implementation spans multiple key components:\n\n1. **Flag Definition (gcc/common.opt:3054)**: The `-fstack-clash-protection` flag is defined as a Common optimization option that 'Insert code to probe each page of stack space as it is allocated to protect from stack-clash style attacks.'\n\n2. **Target Hook Definition (gcc/target.def:6535)**: The `stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range` hook is defined via DEFHOOK mechanism. This hook allows targets to define an ABI-specific interval for stack probing.\n\n3. **Hook Declaration and Default Implementation**: \n   - Declared in gcc/targhooks.h:305 as `extern HOST_WIDE_INT default_stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range (void);`\n   - Implemented in gcc/targhooks.cc:2747 with a default implementation that returns 0\n\n4. **x86_64 Stack Clash Probing (gcc/config/i386/i386.cc:6936)**: The `get_probe_interval()` static function implements x86_64-specific stack clash probing by checking `flag_stack_clash_protection` and using `param_stack_clash_protection_probe_interval` to calculate the probe interval.\n\n5. **Generic Stack Clash Expansion (gcc/explow.cc)**:\n   - `anti_adjust_stack_and_probe()` at line 2201: Generic function for stack probing\n   - `anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash()` at line 2072: Specialized function for stack clash protection using loop-based probing\n   - `compute_stack_clash_protection_loop_data()` at line 1955: Helper function to compute loop data for probing\n   - `emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_start()` at line 2014: Emits the start of the probe loop\n   - `emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_end()` at line 2036: Emits the end of the probe loop\n\n6. **Test Coverage (gcc/testsuite/gcc.target/i386/stack-clash-protection.c)**: A compilation test that verifies stack clash protection code generation with `-fstack-clash-protection` flag.\n\nThe implementation chain flows from the user-facing `-fstack-clash-protection` flag through the target hook infrastructure to architecture-specific implementations (x86_64 via i386.cc) and generic expansion routines (via explow.cc)."
}

